  <div class="section" id="using-the-development-environment">
<h1>Using the Development Environment<a class="headerlink" href="#using-the-development-environment" title="Permalink to this headline">¶</a></h1>
<div class="section" id="installation">
<h2>Installation<a class="headerlink" href="#installation" title="Permalink to this headline">¶</a></h2>
<p>You can find instructions for installing Cream from Git here: <a class="reference external" href="http://cream-project.org/install/">http://cream-project.org/install/</a></p>
</div>
<div class="section" id="activating-the-development-environment">
<h2>Activating the Development Environment<a class="headerlink" href="#activating-the-development-environment" title="Permalink to this headline">¶</a></h2>
<p>You need to run the following command in every console window you want to use the development environment in:</p>
<div class="highlight-bash"><div class="highlight"><pre><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">source </span>dev/bin/activate
</pre></div>
</div>
<p>This will prepend <tt class="docutils literal"><span class="pre">(dev)</span></tt> to your bash prompt to show you, that you are working in a development environment.</p>
</div>
<div class="section" id="running-modules">
<h2>Running Modules<a class="headerlink" href="#running-modules" title="Permalink to this headline">¶</a></h2>
<p>Modules don&#8217;t get installed in your development environment. Commands like <tt class="docutils literal"><span class="pre">melange</span></tt> won&#8217;t work &#8211; unless you have modules installed in your system, too.</p>
<p>Instead, you may find the modules in <tt class="docutils literal"><span class="pre">src/modules</span></tt>. Just change into the particular directory and run the module like this:</p>
<div class="highlight-bash"><div class="highlight"><pre><span class="nv">$ </span><span class="nb">cd </span>src/modules/melange/src
<span class="nv">$ </span>./melange.py
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>


          </div>
      </div>
</div>